Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-41-materials-for-making-mock-up-petticoats-and-crinolines/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-41-materials-for-making-mock-up-petticoats-and-crinolines/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-08T18:51:55+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-08T18:51:55+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 41. Materials for Making Mock-Up Petticoats and Crinolines."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 41. Materials for Making Mock-Up Petticoats and Crinolines."><meta itemprop="description" content="I will teach you how to make mock-up crinolines of different unusual shapes which are impossible to find in stores."><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Practical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. practical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 41. Materials for Making Mock-Up Petticoats and Crinolines.</h1><p><strong>This tutorial will be devoted to a very interesting subject. </strong>I will teach you how to make mock-up crinolines of different unusual shapes which are impossible to find in stores. They are one-of-a-kind crinolines custom-made for a particular garment.</p><p><strong>Let us see what tools you need to make a mock-up crinoline like this. </strong></p><p><strong>Needless to say, a half-scale dress-form will be very handy in this case.</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>If you don’t have a dress-form like this, you can make a replacement from a piece of foam. </strong>Although it resembles the half-scale dress-form very vaguely, it will still allow you to work with the mock-up. Simply roll up a sheet of foam, put it on the dress-form stand, and tie a cord around the waist.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>You will also need a soft mat into which pins can be inserted vertically to secure separate parts of the mock-up in place, etc. </strong></p><p><strong>Puzzle mats are the best choice for this purpose. </strong>But if you don’t have one, you can use any plain soft mat, for example, one made of felted wool, as long as pins can hold well in it. Unfortunately, a pressboard will not do because its surface is simply not large enough.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I will also use the highly popular snap tape. </strong>It is the best material for constructing all kinds of mock-up petticoats.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Another thing we will need is plastic boning sold in rolls. </strong>Of course, you cannot use such boning for real wedding petticoats. It may be suitable for corsets and petticoats made for little girls, and it can be used in swimsuits, bras, and soft dress cups. But it is not robust enough to be used in full-size corsets.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p><p>We need to somehow mark the hoops of our mock-up petticoat so we can differentiate between them in the process. <strong>This can be done with bits of decorative sticky tape or plain masking tape. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I recommend you use wooden pegs with room for making notes to hold hoop ends together.</strong> This way you can not only secure the ends but also number all hoops.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>This is all we need for the mock-up.</strong></p><p>But we will definitely need some additional materials when we finish our mock-up and start working on the full-size petticoat.</p><p><strong>First of all, we will need hoop wire for the hoops of our petticoat. </strong>Hoop wire is made of steel normally covered with a thin coating of plastic. Professional dressmakers usually keep hoop wire of different lengths in stock. I recommend you always take hoops out of old petticoats before throwing them out, too. They will serve you for many years more.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Petersham ribbon is the best material for making tunnels for hoop wire. </strong>It is robust, thick, and easy to work with. You put together two layers and sew them to the petticoat. I avoid using bias tape for hoop tunnels because it is soft and prone to fraying.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The hoop wire is inserted between the two layers of petersham ribbon. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Vertical bridges can be made from wider petersham ribbon or from curtain tape. </strong>The latter is convenient because it has additional guidelines on it, which help you position hoops on the petticoat.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2041.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p><p>You can find rather wide plastic-coated wire in some online corset supplies stores today which could be used as petticoat hoops. &nbsp;I have never used it though because I think it is too strong for our petticoats.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped